				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bards and Shaman unite....<a name="56769"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 15 04 6:07 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I also am a bard/shaman hybird (really dunno why my bard father had a child with a lizard, but hey, whatever does it for ya =p)  It really amazes me the number of hasting classes that don't understand how haste stacks.  I think bards are about the only class that has to have a good understanding of how hastes work.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, I'm just chiming in with all the other shaman/bards who said it's partially a security blanket, and partially a redundancy system.  I just wanted to add a couple of interesting points though.  On the shaman boards, there was a big argument between people who cast the single target (SLtW - 60%) haste vs talisman of alacrity (50%).  Turns out that keeping SLtW up instead of talisman is quite a substantial DPS increase over talisman to classes that are at 40% or less haste. So, next time your shaman casts talisman, tell him that's it's inefficient, and to use SLtW instead. Trust me, he'll love you for this helpful advice, and, coming from a bard, he'll know it to be true.. /nod.
<br />

<br />
Just doing my part for shaman-bard relations.  </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
